<br>
One suggestion a couple of us have come up with is to do away with the fixed points for loot entirely. Make it a closed bid process - you enter a bid up to your total points by tell to the loot master, highest bid (publicly announced after all tells are done) gets the item. This would help ensure that there's a proper value put on nearly every item according to market forces without overly taxing anyone (Desi/Biffins, specifically), should ensure that usuable items never rot (heck, bid 0.1 point on stuff that is MQ'able if you want for guildmates on the off chance that no one will bid anything), and that the inflation of points by raid veterans will have a ready outlet since they have to bid enough points to get the item from someone else who has large numbers of points and removing points from the system and clearing the way for new members. It has the potential of doing away with large numbers of points at once for key drops (bet the farm on Dain's head if you want to get that), allows individuals to set their own values on items (&quot;puller monks&quot; would prefer to spend their points on high AC/HP items and &quot;damage monks&quot; would be spending their points on weapons, for example), and it seems like a lot less headache to run.<br>
<br>
I guess that there WOULD be one chance for, well, undervaluing of items if there's a no-drop class specific item that drops during a raid.  If Abashi's Staff of Disempowerment drops (no-drop, monk &amp; necromancer only weapon off Vulak) and there's only one monk/necromancer present, they'd put in a simple 0.1 bid to get the item and there presumably wouldn't be any competition.  Is that fair?  Dunno.  Perhaps that's why there's a fixed price for items.<br>
<br>
